..TEXT:
The phrase that would make Virgil 'more than father' to Dante,
according to the early commentators, praises his instruction of Dante
in virtue, here redirecting his attention to the immediate task (and
back from mere curiosity, in Carroll's view [comm. to vv. 1-6]).  It
may also reflect the Roman poet's extraordinary ability to bring a
pagan -- and perhaps even this backsliding Christian -- to Christ, as
Statius's narrative has established (and see ^Purg~. XXX.51, Dante's
ultimate gesture of farewell to his 'father': 'Virgil, to whom I gave
myself for my salvation').
