..TEXT:
'O Lord, open my lips, and my mouth shall proclaim your
praise.'  The song of the penitents in Gluttony derives from the
defining moment of David's repentance, not for gluttonous behavior, but
for lust (Psalm 50:17).  For the five other citations of this Psalm in
the ^Commedia~ see Hollander ("Dante's Use of the Fiftieth Psalm,"
^Dante Studies~ 91 [1973], pp. 145-50), who unaccountably did not
include this clear reference.  For the admixture of delight and grief
typical of expressions of penitence on this terrace, see George Andrew
Trone ("The Cry of Dereliction in ^Purgatorio~ XXIII," ^Dante Studies~
113 [1995], 111-29).
Beginning with Jacopo della Lana (comm. to vv. 10-11), commentators
have noted that this verse of the Psalm corrects the former sins of
those who were gluttons because of its insistence on this better use of
mouths -- in songs of praise -- than on the pleasures of the table.
See the clear formulation of this idea in the presentation of Mary as
exemplar of Temperance in the previous canto (^Purg~. XXII.142-144).
