The simile marks these penitents as 'serious,' earnestly
seeking their ritual repentance to seal their salvation.  We are
perhaps reminded that the last two cantos, with their celebration of
the completed purging of a single penitent, were absolutely unusual;
now it is back to business as usual.
At least since the time of Poletto (comm. to these verses)
commentators have thought of Dante's earlier treatment of pilgrims lost
in thought, described in the penultimate sonnet of ^Vita nuova~ (XL.9).
