The entire context of this intimate recollection invites us
to believe that Forese (to leave to one side the question of Dante's
own behavior), in his life on earth, had behaved in ways that suggested
to his friend that his salvation was not exactly to be expected.
Dante's question is amusing.  Since Forese, dead for less than four
years (he died in July of 1296), had lived most of his life a sinner
(and thus was late in his repentance), why did Dante not find him down
on the lower slopes of the mountain in ante-purgatory?  (This is
possibly a sort of compromise, a far more polite question than 'Why did
I not find you in hell?')
