See ^Inferno~ XX.127-129 for the moon being full in the
opening scene of ^Inferno~.  While there is debate (debate so diffuse
and disheveled that one finds Singleton [comm. to vv. 119-120]
translating the word as 'you' and in his commentary saying it means
'there') as to whether the particle ^vi~ (which may mean 'there' or
'you') here refers to the dark wood of ^Inferno~ I or to the penitents
on this mountain, our translation follows Daniello (comm. to vv.
119-120) in accepting the first possibility.  We are reminded that the
action of the poem began on a Friday and that it is now Tuesday
afternoon, the fifth day of the journey.
