With regard to the phrases ^veri morti~ and ^vera carne~,
Antonino Pagliaro (^Ulisse~: ^ricerche semantiche sulla "Divina
Commedia"~ [Messina-Florence: D'Anna, 1967]), p. 654n., points out that
on occasion, as here, Dante uses the adjective ^vero~ as indicating
that 'behind an apparent reality lies an absolute reality,' in this
case because the dead in hell are ^really~ dead for having lost God,
while Dante's flesh is ^really~ flesh (while the 'flesh' of the
penitents is only apparent).
